# Testing Rules

- Every test must assert something meaningful about behavior, not just that code runs without error.
- Unit tests: fast, isolated, no I/O. Use fixtures for shared setup.
- Integration tests: can use filesystem, can use pre-recorded LLM responses.
- Evaluation tests: run metrics on golden dataset, assert scores above threshold.
- For calculation tests: verify against hand-calculated values with known inputs.
- For retrieval tests: verify that the correct document sections are retrieved for domain queries.
- For citation tests: verify that every claim in the response maps to a specific retrieved chunk.
- For refusal tests: verify the system refuses when given queries outside its knowledge.
- NEVER mock the core pipeline in integration tests. Use recorded responses or synthetic data.
- Parametrize calculation tests across multiple materials, temperatures, and vessel geometries.
- Test edge cases: temperature interpolation, boundary conditions (P = 0.385SE exactly), missing data.
